  <h2>The challenge</h2>
  <p>In fall 2022, home energy management systems were an emerging category and GM was entering it for the first time. There was no ecommerce presence, no established journey, and no agreed definition of who the customer even was.</p>
  <p>The engagement began as a service design project with four goals: define how GM Energy should engage with and serve its customers; identify the systems, platforms, and processes needed to enable that experience; craft a future-state vision through concepts and prototypes; and develop the roadmap to bring it to life. The work wasn't redesigning an experience — it was deciding what the experience should be, then carrying it to launch and beyond.</p>

  <h2>Research: understanding the ecosystem and the product line</h2>
  <p>With nothing to audit, research had to build the ground truth — and the first job was simply to understand two things: the ecosystem GM Energy was stepping into, and the product line itself. I went into the field: GM dealerships to experience the electric offering firsthand, competitor EV dealerships, and generator dealers to learn how home backup power actually gets sold today — all alongside desk research across GM's existing consumer and brand work.</p>
  <p>That fed a categorization exercise: mapping the emerging HEMS products against the customers most likely to want each one. It turned a raw catalog of chargers, storage, and backup hardware into a map of <em>who each product is for</em> — the foundation everything downstream would build on. Throughout, service design workshops kept GM stakeholders building alongside us rather than reviewing from a distance.</p>
  <figure class="wmed"><img src="/assets/img/ecosystem-map.jpg" alt="GM Energy customer scenarios and product ecosystem — each HEMS product mapped to the customers most likely to want it" style="width:100%;border-radius:8px;border:1px solid var(--hair);display:block" loading="lazy" />
  <figcaption>Customer scenarios × product ecosystem — mapping every HEMS product to who it's for, with the cross-sell sequence between them.</figcaption></figure>

  <h2>From a master blueprint to detailed journeys</h2>
  <p>That understanding became a large end-to-end service blueprint covering the full lifecycle — learn, shop, buy, install, own. For every customer step it mapped the touchpoints, the frontstage staff actions, and the backstage machinery: which teams, which platforms, which support processes had to exist for that moment to work. For a company standing up commerce, an installer network, and financing all at once, the blueprint became the organization's shared source of truth for what had to be built — and it kept being revised for years as reality caught up with the vision.</p>
  <p>Momentum mattered more than certainty here. In a category no one had mapped yet, waiting for perfect data would have stalled everything — so we made our assumptions explicit and kept moving, treating the blueprint as <em>a living hypothesis, not a finished truth</em>. Every assumption became something to test: usability studies and surveys probed the riskiest ones, and incoming research — the audience segmentation especially — was absorbed the moment it landed, confirming or overturning what we'd sketched. That discipline of assume-then-validate is what let a zero-to-one map stay honest as the real product took shape.</p>
  <p>The master map showed the whole system, but the real design work lived in the columns. I pulled individual columns out of the blueprint — checkout and financing especially — and expanded each into its own detailed journey map, married to the user personas so a map showed not just <em>what</em> happens at a step, but <em>who</em> it's happening to and how it feels. That's where a wall-sized diagram turned into decisions a team could design against.</p>
  <figure class="jmap"><img src="/assets/img/checkout-journey.jpg" alt="The checkout section highlighted on the master blueprint and expanded into a detailed journey in a working session" style="width:100%;border-radius:8px;border:1px solid var(--hair);display:block" loading="lazy" />
  <figcaption>The checkout section spotlighted on the master blueprint and worked into its own detailed journey in a live session — where the checkout design and wireframing began. Shown at scale; detail intentionally not legible.</figcaption></figure>

  <h2>One blueprint, many journeys</h2>
